’Щ@478c601e52ee8657672ca9e5890b206fbd6f91e17f2bdd505ef8527e9570690bЪӢTitle: title: where
Path: Examples
Content:
Filter rows of a table according to a condition.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [{a: 1} {a: 2}] | where a > 1
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ # в”Ӯ a в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
List only the files in the current directory.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where type == file


```
List all files in the current directory with sizes greater than 2kb.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where size > 2kb


```
List all files with names that contain "Car".
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where name =~ "Car"


```
List all files that were modified in the last two weeks.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where modified >= (date now) - 2wk


```
Filter items of a list with a row condition.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1 2 3 4 5] | where $it > 2
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
Filter items of a list with a closure.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1 2 3 4 5] | where {|x| $x > 2 }
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
Find files whose filenames don't begin with the correct sequential number.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where type == file | sort-by name --natural | enumerate | where {|e| $e.item.name !~ $'^($e.index + 1)' } | get item


```
Find case-insensitively files called "readme", with a subexpression inside the row condition.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where ($it.name | str downcase) =~ readme


```
Find case-insensitively files called "readme", with regex only.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> ls | where name =~ '(?i)readme'


```
Filter rows of a table according to a stored condition.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let cond = {|x| $x.a > 1}; [{a: 1} {a: 2}] | where $cond
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ # в”Ӯ a в”Ӯ
в”ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
List all numbers above 3, using an existing closure condition.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> let a = {$in > 3}; [1, 2, 5, 6] | where $a
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 6 в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ


```
’Щ@e6c3215b7a554056d0d48afe91fd874eeaba0279fa0acaee79a6a6909791695bЪөTitle: title: where
Path: Notes
Content:
A condition is evaluated for each element of the input, and only elements which meet the condition are included in the output.
A condition can be either a "row condition" or a closure. A row condition is a special short-hand syntax to makes accessing fields easier.

Each element of the input can be accessed through the 
``$it``
 variable.
On the left hand side of a row condition, any field name is automatically expanded to use 
``$it``
.

For example, 
``where type == dir``
 is equivalent to 
``where $it.type == dir``
. This expansion does not happen when passing a subexpression or closure to 
``where``
.
When using a closure, the element is passed as an argument and as pipeline input (
``$in``
) to the closure. Unlike row conditions, the 
``$it``
 variable isn't available inside closures.
Row conditions cannot be stored in a variable. To pass a condition with a variable, use a closure instead.
